uk.gov.gchq.palisade.example.perf

Class PerfCollector

  • java.lang.Object
    • uk.gov.gchq.palisade.example.perf.PerfCollector

  • public class PerfCollector
extends java.lang.Object
    An output collector receives timing data from performance tests and stores them. It can later be called on to write summary statistics to various outputs.

      • outputTo

        public void outputTo(java.io.OutputStream out,
                     java.util.Map<java.lang.String,java.util.Optional<java.lang.String>> normalMap)
        Writes a table of summary statistics to the given OutputStream. The output stream will not be closed when this method finishes. There will be a normalisation column, this will show the performance of each test relative to the mean of a specific test. The map given details the names of which trials should have their times normalised against which others. For example, if one test had a 2 second mean its the normalised test had a 1 second mean, then the normalised performance will be 2.
        Parameters:
        normalMap - the map of which test names to normalise against which others
        out - where to write output

      • computePerfStats

        public static PerfCollector.PerfStats computePerfStats(java.util.List<java.lang.Long> results)
        Compute the performance statistics for the given list of results. A PerfCollector.PerfStats object is returned containing the results. All times in the given list must be in nanoseconds. The results are converted into seconds. Percentiles are calculated using the linear interpolation closest-rank method.
        Parameters:
        results - the list of results
        Returns:
        performance statistics data

      • computePercentile

        public static double computePercentile(double[] data,
                                       double percentile)
        Computes a given percentile from a sorted list of data. This uses the linear interpolated closest-rank method to calculate percentiles. If the list is not already sorted into ascending order, then the results are undefined,.
        Parameters:
        data - the sorted data
        percentile - the desired percentile, must be in range [0,100]
        Returns:
        the percentile result
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if percentile is out of range, or data is empty
